A Senate committee has adopted all the recommendations of the Auditor General&rsquo;s 2013-14 report.This means county officials accused of embezzlement will be held responsible.The Public Accounts and Investments Committee said it will write a report recommending the DPP, DCI and the Ethics and Anti-Corruption Commission take action.Some of the issues raised by the Auditor General were misappropriation and irregular diversion of county funds, lack of documentation to support spending of county funds and contravention of the Public Procurement and Disposal Act.According to the Auditor General&rsquo;s report, proper records of debtors were not kept and there was no evidence of efforts to recover lost cash.Kakemega Governor Wycliffe Oparanya failed to appear before the committee to answer querries.&ldquo;All governors have appeared before this committee and have responded to the queries as raised by the Auditor General. It is unfortunate Oparanya has totally refused to appear. He should know the people of Kakamega have a right to know where the money went to,&rdquo; Committee chairman John Lonyangapuo said at Parliament Buildings.Senators Kimani Wamatangi (Kiambu), Boni Khalwale (Kakamega) and Liza Chelule (nominated) said Opranya is not above the law and should be held responsible.Bungoma Governor Kenneth Lusaka was taken to task over the 152 accounts operated the county government.